### Description

Functions for data augmentation using the Bayesian discount prior function for 1 arm and 2 arm clinical trials.

### CRAN Installation

Install release version from CRAN:

```R
install.packages("bayesDP")
```

### GitHub Installation

Install development version from GitHub:

```R
devtools::install_github("balcomes/bayesDP")
```

### Documentation 

See manuals and vignettes within package.

### Examples

See manuals and vignettes within package.

<div id="introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>Introduction</h1>
<p>The purpose of this vignette is to introduce the <code>bdpnormal</code> function. <code>bdpnormal</code> is used for estimating posterior samples from a Gaussian mean outcome for clinical trials where an informative prior is used. In the parlance of clinical trials, the informative prior is derived from historical data. The weight given to the historical data is determined using what we refer to as a discount function. There are three steps in carrying out estimation:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>Estimation of the historical data weight, denoted <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span>, via the discount function</p></li>
<li><p>Estimation of the posterior distribution of the current data, conditional on the historical data weighted by <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span></p></li>
<li><p>If a two-arm clinical trial, estimation of the posterior treatment effect, i.e., treatment versus control</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Throughout this vignette, we use the terms <code>current</code>, <code>historical</code>, <code>treatment</code>, and <code>control</code>. These terms are used because the model was envisioned in the context of clinical trials where historical data may be present. Because of this terminology, there are 4 potential sources of data:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>Current treatment data: treatment data from a current study</p></li>
<li><p>Current control data: control (or other treatment) data from a current study</p></li>
<li><p>Historical control data: treatment data from a previous study</p></li>
<li><p>Historical control data: control (or other treatment) data from a previous study</p></li>
</ol>
<p>If only treatment data is input, the function considers the analysis a one-arm trial. If treatment data + control data is input, then it is considered a two-arm trial.</p>
<div id="estimation-of-the-historical-data-weight" class="section level2">
<h2>Estimation of the historical data weight</h2>
<p>In the first estimation step, the historical data weight <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is estimated. In the case of a two-arm trial, where both treatment and control data are available, an <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> value is estimated separately for each of the treatment and control arms. Of course, historical treatment or historical control data must be present, otherwise <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is not estimated for the corresponding arm.</p>
<p>When historical data are available, estimation of <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is carried out as follows. Let <span class="math inline">\(\bar{y}_t\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(s_t\)</span>, and <span class="math inline">\(N_t\)</span> denote the sample mean, sample standard deviation, and sample size of the current data, respectively. Similarly, let <span class="math inline">\(\bar{y}_{0t}\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(s_{0t}\)</span>, and <span class="math inline">\(N_{0t}\)</span> denote the sample mean, sample standard deviation, and sample size of the historical data, respectively. Then, the posterior distribution of the mean for current data, under vague (flat) priors is</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[ <p align="center"><img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/16fcfd4148dcbe0a8bc64e8b2fa817b2.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=380.34975pt height=69.698475pt/></p>
\]</span></p>
<p>Similarly, the posterior distribution of the mean for historical data, under vague (flat) priors is <span class="math display">\[ <p align="center"><img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/7d82d2ba619466decb12b2fadac20836.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=396.50325pt height=69.698475pt/></p>
\]</span></p>
<p>We next compute the posterior probability <span class="math inline">\(p = Pr\left(\tilde{\mu} &lt; \mu_0\right)\)</span>. Finally, for a Weibull distribution function (i.e., the Weibull cumulative distribution function), denoted <span class="math inline">\(W\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is computed as <span class="math display">\[
\hat{\alpha}=<p align="center"><img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/ae17a8b5f48e512504e5bb101020d697.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=268.6266pt height=49.13139pt/></p>
\]</span> where <span class="math inline">\(w_{shape}\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(w_{scale}\)</span> are the shape and scale of the Weibull distribution function, respectively.</p>
<p>There are several model inputs at this first stage. First, the user can select <code>fix_alpha=TRUE</code> and force a fixed value of <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> (at the <code>alpha_max</code> input), as opposed to estimation via the discount function. Next, a Markov Chain Monte Carlo approach is used, requiring several samples from the posterior distributions. Thus, the user can input a sample size greater than or less than the default value of <code>number_mcmc=10000</code>. Finally, the shape of the Weibull discount function can be altered by changing the Weibull shape and scale parameters from the default values of <span class="math inline">\(w_{shape}=3\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(w_{scale}=0.135\)</span> (<code>weibull_shape</code> and <code>weibull_scale</code> inputs).</p>
<p>With the historical data weight <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> in hand, we can move on to estimation of the posterior distribution of the current data.</p>
<div id="discount-function" class="section level3">
<h3>Discount function</h3>
<p>Throughout this vignette, we refer to a discount function. The discount function is a Weibull distribution function and has the form <span class="math display">\[W(x) = 1 - \exp\left\{- (x/w_{scale})^{w_{shape}}\right\}.\]</span> During estimation, a user may be interested in selecting values of <span class="math inline">\(w_{shape}\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(w_{scale}\)</span> that result in optimal statistical properties of the analysis. Thus, the discount function can be used to control the false positive rate (type I error) and/or the false negative rate (type II error). Examples in a following section illustrate the shape of the discount function using the default shape and scale parameters.</p>
<p>Another important aspect related to the discount function is the analysis type: one-sided or two-sided. The sidedness of the analysis is analogous to a one- or two-sided hypothesis test. Using the default shape and scale inputs, a <strong>two-sided</strong> analysis type results in a discount function with the following curve: <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>The discount function of a <strong>one-sided</strong> analysis, again with the default shape and scale inputs, has the following curve: <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>In both of the above plots, the x-axis is the stochastic comparison between current and historical data, which weve denoted <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span>. The y-axis is the discount value <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> that corresponds to a given value of <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span>.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="estimation-of-the-posterior-distribution-of-the-current-data-conditional-on-the-historical-data" class="section level2">
<h2>Estimation of the posterior distribution of the current data, conditional on the historical data</h2>
<p>With <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> in hand, we can now estimate the posterior distribution of the mean of the current data. Using the notation of the previous section, the posterior distribution is <span class="math display">\[\mu \sim \mathcal{N}ormal\left( \frac{\sigma^2_0N_t\bar{y}_t + \tilde{\sigma}^2N_{0t}\bar{y}_{0t}\hat{\alpha}}{N_t\sigma^2_0 + \tilde{\sigma}^2N_{0t}\hat{\alpha}},\,\frac{\tilde{\sigma}^2\sigma^2_0}{N_t\sigma^2_0 + \tilde{\sigma}^2N_{0t}\hat{\alpha}}      \right).\]</span> At this model stage, we have in hand <code>number_mcmc</code> simulations from the augmented mean distribution. If there are no control data, i.e., a one-arm trial, then the modeling stops and we generate summaries of the posterior distribution of <span class="math inline">\(\mu\)</span>. Otherwise, if there are control data, we proceed to a third step and compute a comparison between treatment and control data.</p>
</div>
<div id="estimation-of-the-posterior-treatment-effect-treatment-versus-control" class="section level2">
<h2>Estimation of the posterior treatment effect: treatment versus control</h2>
<p>This step of the model is carried out on-the-fly using the <code>summary</code> or <code>print</code> methods. Let <span class="math inline">\(\mu_T\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(\mu_C\)</span> denote posterior mean estimates of the treatment and control arms, respectively. Currently, the implemented comparison between treatment and control is the difference, i.e., summary statistics related to the posterior difference: <span class="math inline">\(\mu_T - \mu_C\)</span>. In a future release, we may consider implementing additional comparison types.</p>
</div>
<div id="function-inputs" class="section level2">
<h2>Function inputs</h2>
<p>The data inputs for <code>bdpnormal</code> are <code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>, <code>mu0_t</code>, <code>sigma0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>, <code>mu_c</code>, <code>sigma_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>, <code>mu0_c</code>, <code>sigma0_c</code>, and <code>N0_c</code>. The data must be input as (<code>mu</code>, <code>sigma</code>, <code>N</code>) triplets For example, <code>mu_t</code>, the sample mean of the current treatment group, must be accompanied by <code>sigma_t</code> and <code>N_t</code>, the sample standard deviation and sample size, respectively. Historical data inputs are not necessary, but using this function would not be necessary either.</p>
<p><strong>At the minimum, <code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, and <code>N_t</code> must be input</strong>. In the case that only <code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, and <code>N_t</code> are input, the analysis is analogous to a one-sample t-test.. Each of the following input combinations are allowed:</p>
<ul>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) - one-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>mu0_t</code>, <code>sigma0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) - one-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>mu_c</code>, <code>sigma_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>mu0_c</code>, <code>sigma0_c</code>, <code>N0_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>mu0_t</code>, <code>sigma0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) + (<code>mu_c</code>, <code>sigma_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>mu0_t</code>, <code>sigma0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) + (<code>mu0_c</code>, <code>sigma0_c</code>, <code>N0_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>mu_t</code>, <code>sigma_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>mu0_t</code>, <code>sigma0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) + (<code>mu_c</code>, <code>sigma_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>) + (<code>mu0_c</code>, <code>sigma0_c</code>, <code>N0_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="examples" class="section level1">
<h1>Examples</h1>
<div id="one-arm-trial" class="section level2">
<h2>One-arm trial</h2>
<p>Suppose we have historical data with a mean of <code>mu0_t=50</code>, standard deviation of <code>sigma0_t=5</code>, and sample size of <code>N0_t=250</code> patients. Also suppose that we have current data with a mean of <code>mu_t=30</code>, standard deviation of <code>sigma_t=10</code>, and sample size of <code>N_t=250</code>. To illustrate the approach, lets first give full weight to the historical data. This is accomplished by setting <code>alpha_max=1</code> and <code>fix_alpha=TRUE</code> as follows:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">42</span>)
fit1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">bdpnormal</span>(<span class="dt">mu_t      =</span> <span class="dv">30</span>,
                  <span class="dt">sigma_t   =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                  <span class="dt">N_t       =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>, 
                  <span class="dt">mu0_t     =</span> <span class="dv">50</span>,
                  <span class="dt">sigma0_t  =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>,
                  <span class="dt">N0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                  <span class="dt">alpha_max =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>,
                  <span class="dt">fix_alpha =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>)
<span class="kw">summary</span>(fit1)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##     One-armed bdp normal
## 
## data:
##   Current treatment: mu_t = 30, sigma_t = 10, N_t = 250
##   Historical treatment: mu0_t = 50, sigma0_t = 5, N0_t = 250
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - treatment (current vs. historical data): 1
## Discount function value (alpha) - treatment: 1
## 95 percent confidence interval: 
##  44.985  46.922
## augmented sample estimate:
## mean of treatment group
##  45.9982</code></pre>
<p>Based on the <code>summary</code> output of <code>fit1</code>, we can see that the value of <code>alpha</code> was held fixed at 1. The resulting (augmented) mean was estimated at 45.9982. Note that the <code>print</code> and <code>summary</code> methods result in the same output.</p>
<p>Now, lets relax the constraint on fixing <code>alpha</code> at 1. Well also take this opportunity to describe the output of the plot method.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">42</span>)
fit1a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">bdpnormal</span>(<span class="dt">mu_t     =</span> <span class="dv">30</span>,
                   <span class="dt">sigma_t   =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                   <span class="dt">N_t       =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>, 
                   <span class="dt">mu0_t     =</span> <span class="dv">50</span>,
                   <span class="dt">sigma0_t  =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>,
                   <span class="dt">N0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                   <span class="dt">fix_alpha =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>)
<span class="kw">summary</span>(fit1a)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##     One-armed bdp normal
## 
## data:
##   Current treatment: mu_t = 30, sigma_t = 10, N_t = 250
##   Historical treatment: mu0_t = 50, sigma0_t = 5, N0_t = 250
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - treatment (current vs. historical data): 1
## Discount function value (alpha) - treatment: 0
## 95 percent confidence interval: 
##  28.74  31.2272
## augmented sample estimate:
## mean of treatment group
##  29.9963</code></pre>
<p>When <code>alpha</code> is not constrained to one, it is estimated based on a comparison between the current and historical data. We see that the stochastic comparison, <code>p_hat</code>, between historical and control is 1. Here, <code>p_hat</code> is the posterior probability that the current sample mean is less than the historical sample mean under vague priors. With the present example, <code>p_hat = 1</code> implies that the current and historical sample means are very different. The result is that the weight given to the historical data is shrunk towards zero. Thus, the estimate of <code>alpha</code> from the discount function is 0 and the augmented posterior estimate of the mean is approximately the mean of the current data.</p>
<p>Many of the the values presented in the <code>summary</code> method are accessible from the fit object. For instance, <code>alpha</code> is found in <code>fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>alpha_discount</code> and <code>p_hat</code> is located at <code>fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>p_hat</code>. The augmented mean and confidence interval are computed at run-time. The results can be replicated as:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">mean_augmented &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">round</span>(<span class="kw">median</span>(fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>posterior_mu),<span class="dv">4</span>)
CI95_augmented &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">round</span>(<span class="kw">quantile</span>(fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/master/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>posterior_mu, <span class="dt">prob=</span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.025</span>, <span class="fl">0.975</span>)),<span class="dv">4</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p>Finally, well explore the <code>plot</code> method.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">plot</span>(fit1a)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>The top plot displays three density curves. The blue curve is the density of the historical mean, the green curve is the density of the current mean, and the red curve is the density of the current mean augmented by historical data. Since little weight was given to the historical data, the current and posterior means essentially overlap.</p>
<p>The middle plot simply re-displays the posterior mean.</p>
<p>The bottom plot displays the discount function (solid curve) as well as <code>alpha</code> (horizontal dashed line) and <code>p_hat</code> (vertical dashed line). In the present example, the discount function is the Weibull probability distribution with <code>shape=3</code> and <code>scale=0.135</code>.</p>
</div>
<div id="two-arm-trial" class="section level2">
<h2>Two-arm trial</h2>
<p>On to two-arm trials. In this package, we define a two-arm trial as an analysis where a current and/or historical control arm is present. Suppose we have the same treatment data as in the one-arm example, but now we introduce control data: <code>mu_c = 25</code>, <code>sigma_c = 10</code>, <code>N_c = 250</code>, <code>mu0_c = 25</code>, <code>sigma0_c = 5</code>, and <code>N0_c = 250</code>.</p>
<p>Before proceeding, it is worth pointing out that the discount function is applied separately to the treatment and control data. Now, lets carry out the two-arm analysis using default inputs:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">42</span>)
fit2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">bdpnormal</span>(<span class="dt">mu_t      =</span> <span class="dv">30</span>,
                  <span class="dt">sigma_t   =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                  <span class="dt">N_t       =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>, 
                  <span class="dt">mu0_t     =</span> <span class="dv">50</span>,
                  <span class="dt">sigma0_t  =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>,
                  <span class="dt">N0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                  <span class="dt">mu_c      =</span> <span class="dv">25</span>,
                  <span class="dt">sigma_c   =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                  <span class="dt">N_c       =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>, 
                  <span class="dt">mu0_c     =</span> <span class="dv">25</span>,
                  <span class="dt">sigma0_c  =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>,
                  <span class="dt">N0_c      =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                  <span class="dt">fix_alpha =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>)
<span class="kw">summary</span>(fit2)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##     Two-armed bdp normal
## 
## data:
##   Current treatment: mu_t = 30, sigma_t = 10, N_t = 250
##   Current control: mu_c = 25, sigma_c = 10, N_c = 250
##   Historical treatment: mu0_t = 50, sigma0_t = 5, N0_t = 250
##   Historical control: mu0_c = 25, sigma0_c = 5, N0_c = 250
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - treatment (current vs. historical data): 1
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - control (current vs. historical data): 0.5065
## Discount function value (alpha) - treatment: 0
## Discount function value (alpha) - control: 1
## alternative hypothesis:  two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval: 
##  3.6263  6.3496
## augmented sample estimates:
## treatment group  control group
##           30.00          25.00</code></pre>
<p>The <code>summary</code> method of a two-arm analysis is slightly different than a one-arm analysis. First, we see <code>p_hat</code> and <code>alpha</code> reported for the control data. In the present analysis, the current and historical control data have sample means that are very close, thus the historical control data is given full weight. Again, little weight is given to the historical treatment data.</p>
<p>The confidence interval is computed at run time and is the interval estimate of the difference between the posterior means of the treatment and control groups. With a 95% confidence interval of <code>(3.6263, 6.3496)</code>, we would conclude that the treatment and control arms are not significantly different.</p>
<p>The <code>plot</code> method of a two-arm analysis is slightly different than a one-arm analysis as well:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">plot</span>(fit2)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> Each of the three plots are analogous to the one-arm analysis, but each plot now presents additional data related to the control arm.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>Introduction</h1>
<p>The purpose of this vignette is to introduce the <code>bdpbinomial</code> function. <code>bdpbinomial</code> is used for estimating posterior samples from a Binomial event rate outcome for clinical trials where an informative prior is used. In the parlance of clinical trials, the informative prior is derived from historical data. The weight given to the historical data is determined using what we refer to as a discount function. There are three steps in carrying out estimation:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>Estimation of the historical data weight, denoted <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span>, via the discount function</p></li>
<li><p>Estimation of the posterior distribution of the current data, conditional on the historical data weighted by <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span></p></li>
<li><p>If a two-arm clinical trial, estimation of the posterior treatment effect, i.e., treatment versus control</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Throughout this vignette, we use the terms <code>current</code>, <code>historical</code>, <code>treatment</code>, and <code>control</code>. These terms are used because the model was envisioned in the context of clinical trials where historical data may be present. Because of this terminology, there are 4 potential sources of data:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>Current treatment data: treatment data from a current study</p></li>
<li><p>Current control data: control (or other treatment) data from a current study</p></li>
<li><p>Historical control data: treatment data from a previous study</p></li>
<li><p>Historical control data: control (or other treatment) data from a previous study</p></li>
</ol>
<p>If only treatment data is input, the function considers the analysis a one-arm trial. If treatment data + control data is input, then it is considered a two-arm trial.</p>
<div id="estimation-of-the-historical-data-weight" class="section level2">
<h2>Estimation of the historical data weight</h2>
<p>In the first estimation step, the historical data weight <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is estimated. In the case of a two-arm trial, where both treatment and control data are available, an <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> value is estimated separately for each of the treatment and control arms. Of course, historical treatment or historical control data must be present, otherwise <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is not estimated for the corresponding arm.</p>
<p>When historical data are available, estimation of <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is carried out as follows. Let <span class="math inline">\(y\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(N\)</span> denote the number of events and sample size of the current data, respectively. Similarly, let <span class="math inline">\(y_0\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(N_0\)</span> denote the number of events and sample size of the historical data, respectively. Let <span class="math inline">\(a_0\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(b_0\)</span> denote the rate parameters of a Beta distribution. Then, the posterior distributions of the event rates for current and historical data, under vague (flat) priors are</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[ \tilde{\theta} \sim \mathcal{B}eta\left(y+a_0,\,N-y+b_0 \right)\]</span> and</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[ \theta_0 \sim \mathcal{B}eta\left(y_0+a_0,\,N_0-y_0+b_0 \right),\]</span> respectively. We next compute the posterior probability <span class="math inline">\(p = Pr\left(\tilde{\theta} &lt; \theta_0\right)\)</span>. Finally, for a Weibull distribution function (i.e., the Weibull cumulative distribution function), denoted <span class="math inline">\(W\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> is computed as</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\hat{\alpha}=<p align="center"><img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/None/svgs/ae17a8b5f48e512504e5bb101020d697.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=268.6266pt height=49.13139pt/></p>
\]</span> where <span class="math inline">\(w_{shape}\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(w_{scale}\)</span> are the shape and scale of the Weibull distribution function, respectively.</p>
<p>There are several model inputs at this first stage. First, the user can select <code>fix_alpha=TRUE</code> and force a fixed value of <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> (at the <code>alpha_max</code> input), as opposed to estimation via the discount function. Next, a Markov Chain Monte Carlo approach is used, requiring several samples from the posterior distributions. Thus, the user can input a sample size greater than or less than the default value of <code>number_mcmc=10000</code>. Next, the Beta rate parameters can be changed from the defaults of <span class="math inline">\(a_0=b_0=1\)</span> (<code>a0</code> and <code>b0</code> inputs). Finally, the shape of the Weibull discount function can be altered by changing the Weibull shape and scale parameters from the default values of <span class="math inline">\(w_{shape}=3\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(w_{scale}=0.135\)</span> (<code>weibull_shape</code> and <code>weibull_scale</code> inputs).</p>
<p>With the historical data weight <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> in hand, we can move on to estimation of the posterior distribution of the current data.</p>
<div id="discount-function" class="section level3">
<h3>Discount function</h3>
<p>Throughout this vignette, we refer to a discount function. The discount function is a Weibull distribution function and has the form <span class="math display">\[W(x) = 1 - \exp\left\{- (x/w_{scale})^{w_{shape}}\right\}.\]</span> During estimation, a user may be interested in selecting values of <span class="math inline">\(w_{shape}\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(w_{scale}\)</span> that result in optimal statistical properties of the analysis. Thus, the discount function can be used to control the false positive rate (type I error) and/or the false negative rate (type II error). Examples in a following section illustrate the shape of the discount function using the default shape and scale parameters.</p>
<p>Another important aspect related to the discount function is the analysis type: one-sided or two-sided. The sidedness of the analysis is analogous to a one- or two-sided hypothesis test. Using the default shape and scale inputs, a <strong>two-sided</strong> analysis type results in a discount function with the following curve: <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>The discount function of a <strong>one-sided</strong> analysis, again with the default shape and scale inputs, has the following curve: <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>In both of the above plots, the x-axis is the stochastic comparison between current and historical data, which weve denoted <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span>. The y-axis is the discount value <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> that corresponds to a given value of <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span>.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="estimation-of-the-posterior-distribution-of-the-current-data-conditional-on-the-historical-data" class="section level2">
<h2>Estimation of the posterior distribution of the current data, conditional on the historical data</h2>
<p>With <span class="math inline">\(\hat{\alpha}\)</span> in hand, we can now estimate the posterior distribution of the current data event rate. Using the notation of the previous section, the posterior distribution is <span class="math display">\[\theta \sim \mathcal{B}eta\left(y+y_0\hat{\alpha}+a_0,\, N-y+\hat{\alpha}(N_0-y_0)+b_0 \right).\]</span> At this model stage, we have in hand <code>number_mcmc</code> simulations from the augmented event rate distribution. If there are no control data, i.e., a one-arm trial, then the modeling stops and we generate summaries of the posterior distribution of <span class="math inline">\(\theta\)</span>. Otherwise, if there are control data, we proceed to a third step and compute a comparison between treatment and control data.</p>
</div>
<div id="estimation-of-the-posterior-treatment-effect-treatment-versus-control" class="section level2">
<h2>Estimation of the posterior treatment effect: treatment versus control</h2>
<p>This step of the model is carried out on-the-fly using the <code>summary</code> or <code>print</code> methods. Let <span class="math inline">\(\theta_T\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(\theta_C\)</span> denote posterior event rate estimates of the treatment and control arms, respectively. Currently, the implemented comparison between treatment and control is the difference, i.e., summary statistics related to the posterior difference: <span class="math inline">\(\theta_T - \theta_C\)</span>. In a future release, we may consider implementing additional comparison types.</p>
</div>
<div id="function-inputs" class="section level2">
<h2>Function inputs</h2>
<p>The data inputs for <code>bdpbinomial</code> are <code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>, <code>y0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>, <code>y_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>, <code>y0_c</code>, and <code>N0_c</code>. The data must be input as (<code>y</code>, <code>N</code>) pairs. For example, <code>y_t</code>, the number of events in the current treatment group, must be accompanied by <code>N_t</code>, the sample size of the current treatment group. Historical data inputs are not necessary, but using this function would not be necessary either.</p>
<p><strong>At the minimum, <code>y_t</code> and <code>N_t</code> must be input</strong>. In the case that only <code>y_t</code> and <code>N_t</code> are input, the analysis is analogous to using <code>prop.test</code>. Each of the following input combinations are allowed:</p>
<ul>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) - one-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>y0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) - one-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>y_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>y0_c</code>, <code>N0_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>y0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) + (<code>y_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>y0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) + (<code>y0_c</code>, <code>N0_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
<li>(<code>y_t</code>, <code>N_t</code>) + (<code>y0_t</code>, <code>N0_t</code>) + (<code>y_c</code>, <code>N_c</code>) + (<code>y0_c</code>, <code>N0_c</code>) - two-arm trial</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="examples" class="section level1">
<h1>Examples</h1>
<div id="one-arm-trial" class="section level2">
<h2>One-arm trial</h2>
<p>Suppose we have historical data with <code>y0_t=25</code> events out of a sample size of <code>N0_t=250</code> patients. This gives a historical event rate of 0.1. Now, suppose we have current data with <code>y_t=10</code> events out of a sample size of <code>N_t=200</code> patients, giving an event rate of 0.05. To illustrate the approach, lets first give full weight to the historical data. This is accomplished by setting <code>alpha_max=1</code> and <code>fix_alpha=TRUE</code> as follows:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">42</span>)
fit1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">bdpbinomial</span>(<span class="dt">y_t       =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                    <span class="dt">N_t       =</span> <span class="dv">200</span>,
                    <span class="dt">y0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">25</span>,
                    <span class="dt">N0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                    <span class="dt">alpha_max =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>,
                    <span class="dt">fix_alpha =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>)
<span class="kw">summary</span>(fit1)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##     One-armed bdp binomial
## 
## Current treatment data: 10 and 200
## Historical treatment data: 25 and 250
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - treatment (current vs. historical data): 0.9753
## Discount function value (alpha) - treatment: 1
## 95 percent confidence interval: 
##  0.0568  0.1068
## augmented sample estimate:
## probability of success
##  0.0792</code></pre>
<p>Based on the <code>summary</code> output of <code>fit1</code>, we can see that the value of <code>alpha</code> was held fixed at 1. The resulting (augmented) event rate was estimated at 0.0792 which is approximately the event rate if we combined the historical and current data together, i.e., <code>(10 + 25) / (200 + 250) = 0.078</code>. Note that the <code>print</code> and <code>summary</code> methods result in the same output.</p>
<p>Now, lets relax the constraint on fixing <code>alpha</code> at 1. Well also take this opportunity to describe the output of the plot method.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">42</span>)
fit1a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">bdpbinomial</span>(<span class="dt">y_t       =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                     <span class="dt">N_t       =</span> <span class="dv">200</span>,
                     <span class="dt">y0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">25</span>,
                     <span class="dt">N0_t      =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                     <span class="dt">alpha_max =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>,
                     <span class="dt">fix_alpha =</span> <span class="ot">FALSE</span>)
<span class="kw">summary</span>(fit1a)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##     One-armed bdp binomial
## 
## Current treatment data: 10 and 200
## Historical treatment data: 25 and 250
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - treatment (current vs. historical data): 0.9753
## Discount function value (alpha) - treatment: 0.0061
## 95 percent confidence interval: 
##  0.0282  0.0901
## augmented sample estimate:
## probability of success
##  0.0535</code></pre>
<p>When <code>alpha</code> is not constrained to one, it is estimated based on a comparison between the current and historical data. We see that the stochastic comparison, <code>p_hat</code>, between historical and control is 0.9762. Here, <code>p_hat</code> is the posterior probability that the current event rate is less than the historical event rate under vague priors. With the present example, <code>p_hat = 0.9762</code> implies that the current and historical event rates are very different. The result is that the weight given to the historical data is shrunk towards zero. Thus, the estimate of <code>alpha</code> from the discount function is 0.0061, essentially zero, and the augmented posterior estimate of the event rate is approximately the event rate of 0.05 observed in the current data.</p>
<p>Many of the the values presented in the <code>summary</code> method are accessible from the fit object. For instance, <code>alpha</code> is found in <code>fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/None/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>alpha_discount</code> and <code>p_hat</code> is located at <code>fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/None/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>p_hat</code>. The augmented probability of success and confidence interval are computed at run-time. The results can be replicated as:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">mean_augmented &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">round</span>(<span class="kw">median</span>(fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/None/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>posterior),<span class="dv">4</span>)
CI95_augmented &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">round</span>(<span class="kw">quantile</span>(fit1a<img src="https://rawgit.com/balcomes/bayesDP/None/svgs/09f92d7f2c190fd7a60111b4708bea0e.svg?invert_in_darkmode" align=middle width=139.786185pt height=21.60213pt/>posterior, <span class="dt">prob=</span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.025</span>, <span class="fl">0.975</span>)),<span class="dv">4</span>)</code></pre></div>
<p>Finally, well explore the <code>plot</code> method.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">plot</span>(fit1a)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>The top plot displays three density curves. The blue curve is the density of the historical event rate, the green curve is the density of the current event rate, and the red curve is the density of the current event rate augmented by historical data. Since little weight was given to the historical data, the current and posterior event rates essentially overlap.</p>
<p>The middle plot simply re-displays the posterior event rate.</p>
<p>The bottom plot displays the discount function (solid curve) as well as <code>alpha</code> (horizontal dashed line) and <code>p_hat</code> (vertical dashed line). In the present example, the discount function is the Weibull probability distribution with <code>shape=3</code> and <code>scale=0.135</code>.</p>
</div>
<div id="two-arm-trial" class="section level2">
<h2>Two-arm trial</h2>
<p>On to two-arm trials. In this package, we define a two-arm trial as an analysis where a current and/or historical control arm is present. Suppose we have the same treatment data as in the one-arm example, but now we introduce control data: <code>y_c = 15</code>, <code>N_c = 200</code>, <code>y0_c = 20</code>, and <code>N0_c = 250</code>. This control data gives a current event rate of <code>15/200 = 0.075</code> and a historical event rate of <code>20/250 = 0.08</code>.</p>
<p>Before proceeding, it is worth pointing out that the discount function is applied separately to the treatment and control data. Now, lets carry out the two-arm analysis using default inputs:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">42</span>)
fit2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">bdpbinomial</span>(<span class="dt">y_t  =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>,
                    <span class="dt">N_t  =</span> <span class="dv">200</span>,
                    <span class="dt">y0_t =</span> <span class="dv">25</span>,
                    <span class="dt">N0_t =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>,
                    <span class="dt">y_c  =</span> <span class="dv">15</span>,
                    <span class="dt">N_c  =</span> <span class="dv">200</span>,
                    <span class="dt">y0_c =</span> <span class="dv">20</span>,
                    <span class="dt">N0_c =</span> <span class="dv">250</span>)
<span class="kw">summary</span>(fit2)</code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##     Two-armed bdp binomial
## 
## Current treatment data: 10 and 200
## Current control data: 15 and 200
## Historical treatment data: 25 and 250
## Historical control data: 20 and 250
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - treatment (current vs. historical data): 0.9753
## Stochastic comparison (p_hat) - control (current vs. historical data): 0.5715
## Discount function value (alpha) - treatment: 0.0061
## Discount function value (alpha) - control: 1
## alternative hypothesis:  two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   -0.0628 0.0161
## augmented sample estimates:
## prop 1 prop2
##   0.05  0.08</code></pre>
<p>The <code>summary</code> method of a two-arm analysis is slightly different than a one-arm analysis. First, we see <code>p_hat</code> and <code>alpha</code> reported for the control data. In the present analysis, the current and historical control data have event rates that are very close, thus the historical control data is given full weight. This implies that the (augmented) posterior control event rate is approximately <code>(15 + 20)/(200 + 250) = 0.08</code>. Again, little weight is given to the historical treatment data, so we have an (augmented) posterior treatment event rate of approximately 0.05.</p>
<p>The confidence interval is computed at run time and is the interval estimate of the difference between the posterior treatment and control event rates. With a 95% confidence interval of <code>(-0.0628, 0.0161)</code>, we would conclude that the treatment and control arms are not significantly different.</p>
<p>The <code>plot</code> method of a two-arm analysis is slightly different than a one-arm analysis as well:</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span class="kw">plot</span>(fit2)</code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="60%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> Each of the three plots are analogous to the one-arm analysis, but each plot now presents additional data related to the control arm.</p>
</div>
</div>
